<h1>8 Steps of Adoption</h1>
<p class="subhead">Placing a child for adoption is a big decision and one that should not be made without careful<br /> consideration. Birth parents should be well prepared for the complex impact of legally relinquishing<br /> a child since this is a permanent decision. Whether you are pregnant or your child is already born,<br /> adoption is a loving option.</p>
<p>The following is a brief step-by-step process of adoption:</p>
<h2><span class="subtle">Step 1</span> Seek Counseling</h2>
<p>Every woman facing an unplanned pregnancy needs support and an objective person to talk to.<br /> If you don&rsquo;t have someone in your life that can offer sound advice during this challenging time,<br /> seek professional assistance. Often the adoption agency or adoption attorney you work with will<br /> connect you with counseling resources in your area at no cost to you.</p>
<h2><span class="subtle">Step 2</span> Identity an Adoption Service Provider</h2>
<p>There are many qualified and reputable agencies and attorneys that specialize in adoption.<br /> Be sure to do your research and make sure what they have to offer in services will meet your<br /> needs. For example, do they provide you with a social worker or case manager that can be<br /> available when you need help? Is it important to you that they be local so you can meet<br /> face to face? Do they provide the level of support and information you need to be<br /> fully informed about adoption?</p>
<p>In some cases, women considering adoption choose to identify an adoptive family for their child                             before selecting an adoption service provider. That&rsquo;s okay to do. Something to remember, though,                             until you are working with an agency or attorney, you may not have the support of experienced                             adoption professionals to help. Your adoption service provider may also work with you on meeting                             your practical needs such as housing, living expense assistance, and medical care to name a few.</p>
<h2><span class="subtle">Step 3</span> Make an Adoption Plan</h2>
<p>Work with your adoption service provider to  outline your expectations for placing your child for adoption. Make your  choices and preferences known.  If the agency is assisting you with  selecting a family, this is also the time to list the qualities and  characteristics you&rsquo;d like the adoptive family to have.  Your adoption  plan also typically addresses your childbirth and hospital experience,  as well as current and on-going contact with the adoptive family.</p>
<h2><span class="subtle">Step 4</span> Select an Adoptive Family</h2>
<p>ParentFinder.com has hundreds of adoptive  families to choose from. You can search by specific religions, regions  or by family structure. It&rsquo;s likely that whatever you are looking for in  an adoptive family, you&rsquo;ll be able to find here without looking  further.</p>
<div class="banner photo"><a href="http://www.parentfinder.com/page/8 Steps of Adoption"> <span>Just click to view waiting adoptive families.</span> <img src="http://www.wordes.org/parentfinder/img/pages/home/circle_arrow.png" /> </a></div>
<h2><span class="subtle">Step 5</span> Birth and Relinquishment of Your Child</h2>
<p>You define your hospital experience. The  time until you sign relinquishment paperwork, is your time. You decide  who to have with you at the hospital and the level of bonding and  contact you will have with your child. According to the hospital plan  you develop, the adoptive family should be well aware of your requests  during this time and respect your wishes. It&rsquo;s important to know, in  many states, once relinquishment documents are signed, there is no  revocation period to change your mind or &ldquo;undo&rdquo; the adoption.</p>
<h2><span class="subtle">Step 6</span> Placement of Your Child</h2>
<p>Each state differs in their adoption laws;  however, typically the child is placed with the adoptive family shortly  after birth. In most states, the baby is placed upon discharge from the  hospital at birth.</p>
<h2><span class="subtle">Step 7</span> Legal Finalization of the Adoption</h2>
<p>Again, each state varies but typically  within 3 to 6 months, most adoptions are finalized. This means the  adoption becomes final and the adoptive family becomes the permanent and  official parent(s) of the child.</p>
<h2><span class="subtle">Step 8</span> Take Time for Yourself</h2>
<p>Understand that you will most likely feel  some grief and loss over the adoption of your child. Take time to  recover and seek support from your family and friends. Accept that you  have made a very difficult decision and take time to heal.</p>
