<h1>Unplanned Pregnancy?</h1>
<p>As a general statistic, it is estimated that  up to 49 percent of the pregnancies in the U.S. are unplanned.<br /> This includes pregnancies happening both inside marriage (or committed relationships) and those<br /> happening to single women. In fact, one study shows that 48 percent of women under age 44 have<br /> been through an unplanned pregnancy at some point in their lives.</p>
<p>If you are facing an unintended pregnancy and aren&rsquo;t sure what to do, we strongly encourage<br /> you seek counseling to explore all your options. We know that no decision will be made easily,<br /> so be sure to educate yourself about possible choices. Whether parenting, adoption or<br /> abortion is your final decision, we respect your choice.</p>
<h2>Parenting</h2>
<p>There are several options when it comes to parenting. Will you parent the child alone?<br /> Will you marry the father of the baby? Will you jointly parent the child but choose not<br /> to marry? There is a great deal to think about when considering parenting. Parenting is<br /> often described as the most rewarding experience for a mother, but also the most challenging.</p>
<p>Some things to consider:</p>
<ul>
<li>What type of support would the father of the baby provide?</li>
<li>Could your family help with financial, childcare or living arrangements?</li>
<li>What would it take to live on your own with your baby?</li>
<li>How will you continue to reach your goals to make a better life for yourself and your child?</li>
</ul>
<h2>Adoption</h2>
<p>Did you know that 60% of Americans had a personal experience with adoption, meaning that they<br /> themselves, a family member, or a close friend was adopted, had adopted a child, or had placed<br /> a child for adoption. According to the US Census (2000), there are over one and a half million<br /> adopted children under the age of 18. With adoption being so common, it has also become increasingly<br /> common for birth and adoptive families to have some form of direct contact after placement.<br /> This practice is called "open adoption," but the degree of openness can vary significantly. Birth<br /> and adoptive parents may meet before the adoption is finalized and have no further contact, or the<br /> families may maintain some level of ongoing contact throughout the child\'s life, such as exchanging<br /> photos or letters or having face-to-face meetings. Adoption is a widely accepted alternative to<br /> parenting and abortion and can bring great joy and love to an adoptive family and child, while<br /> allowing a birth family the opportunity to remain connected to their biological child while working<br /> to improve their own situation and focus on life goals.</p>
<p>Did you know that in adoption:</p>
<ul>
<li>You can choose the adoptive family and many preferences for your child\'s future.</li>
<li>You can define what you would like your relationship to be with your child and the adoptive family.</li>
<li>More and more adoptive parents explain  adoption to the child at each stage of development in order to become  well-adjusted, successful individuals.</li>
<li>At any point before you place the child  with an adoptive family, you may decide to parent regardless of any  assistance you may have received.</li>
<li>There are free resources (counseling,  support groups and other services) available to help you work through  the grieving process, issues of loss and challenges along the way.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Abortion</h2>
<p>Abortion means ending a pregnancy. Given that  unintended pregnancy is an issue that affects thousands of people each  year, abortion is one of the most common medical procedures performed in  the country. There are several types of abortion procedures, depending  upon the stage of pregnancy. You should be knowledgeable about abortion  facts and various abortion methods available.</p>
